    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>The technique of using a metal rod, usually in a holder, to write or draw on a surface, often paper, parchment, or wood that has been covered by a ground. Ivory is another common support. As the point moves across the surface, it leaves behind a thin layer of the metal, which quickly oxidizes. For example, lines from silver points becomes the brownish grey of tarnished silver and lines from lead points becomes very dark. </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
